The announcement by GÃ©camines, DRC's state mining company, that it will renegotiate all contracts with international miners is part of a wider general trend as African states seek greater economic balance in mining contracts and an increased share of mining revenues. This piece considers some of the renegotiation dynamics at play, and the issues investors and host states will likely consider. As global demand surges for substances such as cobalt, copper, lithium and germanium, Africa's preeminent position as a leader in natural resources will continue. Indeed, the demand for such metals as cobalt and copper is forecast to double over the next few years as new technologies such as lithium-ion batteries used to power the world's electronic cars and portable devices proliferate. 